{      Jacoby 2N      }
^-|HT|g|cp|5|fp|2|AT|
^b@2^*BHoward:|CP||AT| This is the final lesson of 4 on slam bidding. To review, the first 2 lessons were on hand evaluation. They were the most important, as they apply to all auctions, partials, games, and slams. Just as a reminder. If you use Bergen's methods of hand evaluation, you need 26 points between the combined hands to bid game. If you have 33 points or more, you are in the slam range.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT|

However, just because you have 33 points, it does not mean you should automatically bid slam . You need to make sure you do not have 2 losers off the top. That means you  have to have first round control (Ace or void) of 3 suits, and 2nd round control (King or singleton) of the 4th suit.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

Control bids were the topic of the third lesson, last week. In that lesson, I discussed control bids and Roman Key Card Blackwood, which are used to make sure you have the necessary controls in all suits. So, we now have the theoretical foundation about what we need to bid slam, and how to stop if slam cannot be made. |
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


AT|

This week's lesson will be on two common conventions that can help get us to slam,|HT|u|cs|4|FP|2|AT|^C{ ^GJacoby 2N                    }|FP||AT|^m  and |FP|2|AT|^o{                        splinter bids                      }|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


FP||AT|


In addition, I will discuss an interesting and little known convention,|CS|4|FP|2|AT|      {    5N, pick a slam    }|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


CS||FP||AT|

OK, let's start with Jacoby 2N|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
HT|e|cs|5|AT|^-
{      Jacoby 2N      }
^-|HT|g|cp|5|fp|2|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|As most of you know, when partner opens 1 of a major, and you have 4+ card support and a game forcing hand (at least 13 dummy points), you bid 2N to show that hand. That convention is known as |cp|5|at|Jacoby 2N|cp||at|.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT|

Bergen recommends that you always bid 2N with 13+ dummy points and 4 card support. Therefore, if you do not bid Jacoby 2N but show a game forcing hand, and later raise the major, you can only have 3 card support at most. That is an important negative inference. If you do not bid Jacoby 2N after showing a game forcing hand, you cannot have 4 card support of the major. A 9-card trump fit is much better than an 8 card trump fit. It is almost worth an extra trick.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


AT|

So Bergen recommends you tell your partner the good news immediately. The only exception to this is on hands where you have shortness, you can splinter instead of bidding Jacoby 2N. But splinters also show 4 card support and game forcing values. Therefore, absent a splinter or Jacoby 2N, if responder has shown a game forcing hand, he does not have 4+ trump support.|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


AT|

Now, let us look at a few examples. As in the past I show you the hand and the auction. Count the value of the hand and then choose your bid. I will give the correct answer afterward. |
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


